    value: 옥천은 절 이름이요, 각은은 호요, 잠은 이름이다.
english:
  title: An Inscription for the Cloud Pavilion, with Preface
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The vapors of mountain and marsh condense to become clouds. The dragon's breath too can form clouds. For the dragon is the numinous creature of mountain and marsh, and its ability to exhale clouds follows naturally from this affinity of essence. The Book of Changes speaks of clouds ascending to heaven in the hexagram of Water over Heaven—and thus water becomes both cloud and rain, which is abundantly clear. A cloud drifts in the great void, ethereal and floating, unfurling and gathering as it pleases—embodying the wisdom of sages who move freely between engagement and withdrawal from the world. Yet when clouds bestow rain to nourish all things and display their colors to bring blessing to the age, they manifest the sage's way of transformation and nurture. The elder of Jade Spring, Kak-eun Cham, named his dwelling the Cloud Pavilion—though I confess I do not know what principle he wished to capture. If he sought to emulate the sage's withdrawal from the world, he has already surrendered his heart to the Buddha's nirvana. If he sought to follow the sage's transformative way, he has already shed the bonds of human relations. Tao Yuanming wrote: "The cloud departs the mountain with no intent"—for in its purposeless rising, it contends with nothing, which is indeed a marvel of the cloud. Cham then said, "This is precisely what I seek." And so I composed this inscription:

    O cloud sublime! Your nature rests in stillness, yet your will dances in motion—truly you unite both essence and function. Rising upward from below, you become the hope of the people. You traverse the heavens, dispensing rain to nourish the earth beneath. The noble one takes this as his model: perfecting himself while perfecting all things. Luminous Cham Kak-eun finds joy in his modest dwelling. What meaning does naming a pavilion hold? I cherish his self-acquired wisdom. What has he acquired? The abandonment of learning and the cessation of striving—which both Confucians and Buddhists hold supreme. The Confucian finds it there in the cloud's nourishment, the Buddhist here in the cloud's non-attachment. Beyond this, I know not.
  footnotes:
    - Jade Spring (Okcheon) is the name of a temple; Kak-eun (覺隱) is a monastic name; Cham (岑) is the personal name of this Buddhist elder.
    - The reference to 'Water over Heaven' (水天 or the hexagram 需) from the Book of Changes symbolizes clouds gathering in the sky before rain falls.
    - Tao Yuanming (陶淵明), the recluse poet of the Eastern Jin dynasty, represents the ideal of withdrawal from worldly affairs pursued with natural grace.
